WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.475 align:middle line:90%
[WHOOSH]

00:00:02.475 --> 00:00:05.445 align:middle line:90%


00:00:05.445 --> 00:00:07.920 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:12.375 align:middle line:90%


00:00:12.375 --> 00:00:14.850 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:14.850 --> 00:00:31.690 align:middle line:90%


00:00:31.690 --> 00:00:35.480 align:middle line:84%
>> How do we
experience the world?

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:40.410 align:middle line:84%
How do we make sense of it,
measure it, construct it,

00:00:40.410 --> 00:00:42.600 align:middle line:84%
and understand our
position in it?

00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:47.060 align:middle line:90%


00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:50.730 align:middle line:84%
A controversial scientist,
Iain McGilchrist,

00:00:50.730 --> 00:00:52.980 align:middle line:84%
has developed a radical
theory about how

00:00:52.980 --> 00:00:57.520 align:middle line:90%
our brain interprets the world.

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:00.520 align:middle line:84%
>> Iain McGilchrist, he's a
psychiatrist and author of "The

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:02.140 align:middle line:90%
Master and His Emissary--

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:05.860 align:middle line:84%
The Divided Brain and the
Making of the Western World,"

00:01:05.860 --> 00:01:08.710 align:middle line:84%
about the various implications
of the differences

00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:11.720 align:middle line:84%
between the two
hemispheres in the brain.

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:12.520 align:middle line:10%
Let's start there.

00:01:12.520 --> 00:01:13.320 align:middle line:10%
Like what?

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:14.800 align:middle line:10%
>> Two hemispheres have styles--

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:16.360 align:middle line:10%
takes, if you
like-- on the world.

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:17.690 align:middle line:10%
They see things differently.

00:01:17.690 --> 00:01:19.065 align:middle line:10%
They prioritize
different things.

00:01:19.065 --> 00:01:21.310 align:middle line:10%
There are different values.

00:01:21.310 --> 00:01:25.690 align:middle line:84%
The left hemisphere's goal is to
enable us to manipulate things.

00:01:25.690 --> 00:01:27.460 align:middle line:84%
Whereas, the goal of
the right hemisphere

00:01:27.460 --> 00:01:31.015 align:middle line:84%
is to relate to things and
understand them as a whole.

00:01:31.015 --> 00:01:33.640 align:middle line:84%
Two ways of thinking
that are both needed,

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:37.990 align:middle line:84%
but are fundamentally at
the same time incompatible.

00:01:37.990 --> 00:01:42.850 align:middle line:84%
>> McGilchrist claims that the
left hemisphere of the brain is

00:01:42.850 --> 00:01:46.420 align:middle line:84%
gradually colonizing our
experience of the world with

00:01:46.420 --> 00:01:49.520 align:middle line:84%
potentially disastrous
implications.

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:51.760 align:middle line:84%
>> The way of thinking
which is reductive,

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:54.640 align:middle line:90%
mechanistic has taken us over.

00:01:54.640 --> 00:01:58.960 align:middle line:84%
We behave like people who
had right hemisphere damage.

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:04.550 align:middle line:10%
>> Do we pay a price for being
too left hemisphere-centered?

00:02:04.550 --> 00:02:06.190 align:middle line:10%
>> We may pay the
ultimate price,

00:02:06.190 --> 00:02:10.419 align:middle line:10%
who treats the world as a
simple resource to be exploited.

00:02:10.419 --> 00:02:12.280 align:middle line:84%
It's made us
enormously powerful.

00:02:12.280 --> 00:02:15.400 align:middle line:84%
It's enabled us
to become wealthy.

00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:19.300 align:middle line:84%
But it's also meant
that we've lost means

00:02:19.300 --> 00:02:21.010 align:middle line:90%
to understand the world.

00:02:21.010 --> 00:02:24.430 align:middle line:10%
>> His revolutionary theory has
attracted prominent supporters

00:02:24.430 --> 00:02:28.180 align:middle line:10%
worldwide, comparing
him to Freud and Darwin.

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:31.660 align:middle line:10%
>> I think "The Master and
His Emissary" was possibly,

00:02:31.660 --> 00:02:33.395 align:middle line:10%
one of the most
important books I read.

00:02:33.395 --> 00:02:35.770 align:middle line:10%
>> The idea that there is a
distinction between those two

00:02:35.770 --> 00:02:40.180 align:middle line:10%
perspectives seems,
to me, correct.

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:42.640 align:middle line:10%
And I see it all the
time in my own field

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:44.020 align:middle line:10%
of clinical psychology.

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:46.360 align:middle line:10%
>> I kind of had one
revelation after another.

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:49.420 align:middle line:10%
I mean, it just explains an
incredible number of things

00:02:49.420 --> 00:02:52.480 align:middle line:10%
that I've always been
slightly positive about.

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:55.580 align:middle line:84%
>> But scientists
think he's a heretic.

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:57.230 align:middle line:90%
>> It's a fantastic book.

00:02:57.230 --> 00:02:59.950 align:middle line:10%
It's a fantastic book
that I don't believe in.

00:02:59.950 --> 00:03:02.390 align:middle line:10%
>> The brain is as
mechanical as clockwork.

00:03:02.390 --> 00:03:04.760 align:middle line:10%
A famous English
physicist said that.

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:07.360 align:middle line:90%
Let's just get over that.

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:09.550 align:middle line:84%
>> Now McGilchrist
is on the road.

00:03:09.550 --> 00:03:12.580 align:middle line:84%
Invited to speak about his
view of the brain and society.

00:03:12.580 --> 00:03:15.730 align:middle line:90%


00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:18.040 align:middle line:84%
Could the problems
of the modern world

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:21.350 align:middle line:84%
be influenced by an
imbalance in the human brain?

00:03:21.350 --> 00:03:24.140 align:middle line:90%


00:03:24.140 --> 00:03:27.980 align:middle line:84%
And what does that
imply about our future?

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:30.410 align:middle line:10%
For Iain McGilchrist,
the problem

00:03:30.410 --> 00:03:36.090 align:middle line:10%
is not only bad politics or
a warped economic system.

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:39.800 align:middle line:84%
The problem is inside
our modern brain.

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:58.648 align:middle line:90%


00:03:58.648 --> 00:04:01.128 align:middle line:90%
[WAVES]

00:04:01.128 --> 00:04:07.110 align:middle line:90%


00:04:07.110 --> 00:04:09.300 align:middle line:10%
>> The landscape speaks
very strongly to people.

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:12.100 align:middle line:90%


00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:16.360 align:middle line:84%
Some people find it a
little bit overwhelming.

00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:18.910 align:middle line:84%
I suspect it's what
the people call

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:21.490 align:middle line:84%
one of their Celtic
thin places, where

00:04:21.490 --> 00:04:24.880 align:middle line:84%
the world beyond the
immediate seems very apparent.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:28.440 align:middle line:90%


00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:32.930 align:middle line:84%
There is something very
special about the whole place.

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:37.520 align:middle line:84%
There's a strong energy there
from the wildness of nature.

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:38.750 align:middle line:90%
You feel it.

00:04:38.750 --> 00:04:42.500 align:middle line:84%
>> It was here that McGilchrist
developed his groundbreaking

00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:43.520 align:middle line:90%
theory.

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:47.600 align:middle line:10%
>> My dad was a doctor and tried
to avoid becoming a doctor.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:50.180 align:middle line:10%
His first degree
was in economics.

00:04:50.180 --> 00:04:52.220 align:middle line:84%
And I rather repeated
the pattern in this.

00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:54.110 align:middle line:84%
I didn't even begin to
be trained in medicine

00:04:54.110 --> 00:04:54.935 align:middle line:90%
until was 28.

00:04:54.935 --> 00:04:57.122 align:middle line:90%
[NON-ENGLISH SINGING]

00:04:57.122 --> 00:04:59.690 align:middle line:90%


00:04:59.690 --> 00:05:03.650 align:middle line:84%
>> McGilchrist took an indirect
path to reach medicine.

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:06.200 align:middle line:10%
As a young man, he
taught literature

00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:09.750 align:middle line:10%
at Oxford University.

00:05:09.750 --> 00:05:12.560 align:middle line:84%
>> After I got my degree, I
got a fellowship at All Souls

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:15.470 align:middle line:84%
College, which enabled me
to do, really, more or less,

00:05:15.470 --> 00:05:17.840 align:middle line:84%
anything I liked
intellectually for seven years.

00:05:17.840 --> 00:05:27.940 align:middle line:90%


00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:31.120 align:middle line:10%
And into that time, I
then ended up really

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:34.930 align:middle line:10%
thinking more about
the mind-body problem.

00:05:34.930 --> 00:05:38.380 align:middle line:84%
When we read a poem or we
listen to a piece of music,

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:41.020 align:middle line:90%
it can bring tears to your eyes.

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:42.520 align:middle line:90%
It can quicken your pulse.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:44.410 align:middle line:84%
It can raise your
blood pressure.

00:05:44.410 --> 00:05:50.180 align:middle line:84%
In other words, it has enormous
effects on you physiologically.

00:05:50.180 --> 00:05:52.460 align:middle line:84%
I felt that we were
doing something

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:55.670 align:middle line:90%
destructive to literature.

00:05:55.670 --> 00:05:57.170 align:middle line:84%
People in the past
had taken trouble

00:05:57.170 --> 00:06:01.460 align:middle line:84%
to create something that was
unique, embodied, and implicit.

00:06:01.460 --> 00:06:03.230 align:middle line:84%
And we came along
and made it general

00:06:03.230 --> 00:06:04.730 align:middle line:90%
and abstract and explicit.

00:06:04.730 --> 00:06:08.940 align:middle line:84%
And making a poem explicit is
a bit like explaining a joke.

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:12.070 align:middle line:90%
It just makes it fall flat.

00:06:12.070 --> 00:06:15.050 align:middle line:84%
A work of art is
an embodied being

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:17.460 align:middle line:84%
that has an encounter with
you as an embodied being.

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:19.910 align:middle line:84%
It's not a bunch of
thought that just has

00:06:19.910 --> 00:06:22.710 align:middle line:90%
an encounter with your brain.

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:26.600 align:middle line:84%
The base of the problem was
the mind-body relationship.

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:28.350 align:middle line:84%
That we were looking
at literature in much

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:30.410 align:middle line:90%
too disembodied a way.

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:32.130 align:middle line:90%
I thought no.

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:36.590 align:middle line:84%
I need somehow to
tackle this problem.

00:06:36.590 --> 00:06:39.246 align:middle line:84%
That was what impelled
me to do medicine.

00:06:39.246 --> 00:06:44.450 align:middle line:90%


00:06:44.450 --> 00:06:48.380 align:middle line:84%
>> McGilchrist spent the next
14 years training in neurology

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:50.030 align:middle line:90%
and psychiatry.

00:06:50.030 --> 00:06:53.030 align:middle line:84%
It was a journey that took
him to the renowned Maudsley

00:06:53.030 --> 00:06:54.610 align:middle line:90%
Hospital in London.

00:06:54.610 --> 00:07:00.290 align:middle line:90%


00:07:00.290 --> 00:07:04.210 align:middle line:84%
>> So this was built just around
the time of the First World

00:07:04.210 --> 00:07:06.700 align:middle line:90%
War.

00:07:06.700 --> 00:07:11.390 align:middle line:84%
This was one of the many places
to which I owe a huge debt.

00:07:11.390 --> 00:07:14.810 align:middle line:84%
Because I was seeing an
extremely broad cross-section

00:07:14.810 --> 00:07:16.130 align:middle line:90%
of patients.

00:07:16.130 --> 00:07:17.930 align:middle line:84%
Conditions such
as schizophrenia,

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:20.375 align:middle line:84%
severe personality
disorders, and head injuries.

00:07:20.375 --> 00:07:24.550 align:middle line:90%


00:07:24.550 --> 00:07:29.430 align:middle line:84%
This is an amazing
painting by William Kurelek

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:30.804 align:middle line:90%
called "The Maze."

00:07:30.804 --> 00:07:40.105 align:middle line:90%


00:07:40.105 --> 00:07:42.880 align:middle line:84%
What's interesting is
the very human anguish

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:45.835 align:middle line:90%
of this person with his illness.

00:07:45.835 --> 00:07:51.470 align:middle line:90%


00:07:51.470 --> 00:07:56.180 align:middle line:84%
What one is seeing is a change
in the whole way in which one

00:07:56.180 --> 00:08:00.455 align:middle line:84%
experiences the world due to
something out of the ordinary

00:08:00.455 --> 00:08:02.125 align:middle line:90%
in brain functioning.

00:08:02.125 --> 00:08:05.310 align:middle line:90%


00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:08.400 align:middle line:10%
Here at the Maudsley
Hospital, I had access

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:13.632 align:middle line:10%
to patients for whom the world
has become utterly changed.

00:08:13.632 --> 00:08:15.090 align:middle line:10%
Particularly
interesting to me were

00:08:15.090 --> 00:08:17.940 align:middle line:10%
people with either
tumors or strokes.

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:21.930 align:middle line:84%
Because there, you can
localize where the damage is.

00:08:21.930 --> 00:08:23.550 align:middle line:10%
You can see it in a scan.

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:27.710 align:middle line:10%
And you can then see what
happens to that patient.

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:31.220 align:middle line:84%
Good science starts from a
really intriguing question.

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:33.919 align:middle line:90%
Why is the brain divided?

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:38.710 align:middle line:84%
You know, I never heard that
asked in any of my training.

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:41.870 align:middle line:84%
It's really what I've been
thinking about all my life.

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:43.880 align:middle line:84%
About these two
different ways in which

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:46.670 align:middle line:90%
we seem to inhabit the world.

00:08:46.670 --> 00:08:50.450 align:middle line:84%
And that was the beginning of a
20-year long process in which I

00:08:50.450 --> 00:08:53.120 align:middle line:84%
tried to apply myself
to the question of what

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:55.550 align:middle line:84%
the differences between these
two hemispheres really were.

00:08:55.550 --> 00:09:04.180 align:middle line:90%


00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:06.400 align:middle line:10%
>> Everything we
human beings ever do,

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:10.150 align:middle line:10%
no matter how ordinary it
seems, has a complex beginning

00:09:10.150 --> 00:09:12.910 align:middle line:10%
in our brains.

00:09:12.910 --> 00:09:14.770 align:middle line:84%
Finding out how the
brain does this work

00:09:14.770 --> 00:09:17.920 align:middle line:84%
is a study that has fascinated
scientists for centuries.

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:20.680 align:middle line:10%
>> The brain is, of course, an
enormously complex structure.

00:09:20.680 --> 00:09:22.850 align:middle line:10%
In fact, it's kind of
redundantly complex.

00:09:22.850 --> 00:09:24.940 align:middle line:10%
We have two cerebral
hemispheres.

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:26.560 align:middle line:84%
But it becomes a
fascinating question

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:29.110 align:middle line:84%
to know whether the two
cerebral hemispheres can

00:09:29.110 --> 00:09:30.250 align:middle line:90%
operate separately.

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:34.040 align:middle line:84%
>> In the '60s and '70s
in California at Caltech,

00:09:34.040 --> 00:09:38.650 align:middle line:84%
there was some incredibly
important and fascinating work.

00:09:38.650 --> 00:09:41.920 align:middle line:84%
And what they were
trying to do was

00:09:41.920 --> 00:09:44.920 align:middle line:84%
to improve the quality
of life for people

00:09:44.920 --> 00:09:46.630 align:middle line:90%
with intractable epilepsy.

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:49.030 align:middle line:84%
Now these people might
have almost continuous

00:09:49.030 --> 00:09:50.800 align:middle line:90%
epileptic seizures.

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:53.530 align:middle line:84%
Which meant that
they couldn't really

00:09:53.530 --> 00:09:57.130 align:middle line:84%
carry on any kind
of normal life.

00:09:57.130 --> 00:10:02.290 align:middle line:84%
>> The original idea was based
on the notion that if you

00:10:02.290 --> 00:10:06.520 align:middle line:84%
isolated a seizure to one
half the brain so it could not

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:10.990 align:middle line:84%
spread to the other half
brain, when a seizure occurred,

00:10:10.990 --> 00:10:13.283 align:middle line:84%
you would prevent a
generalized convulsion.

00:10:13.283 --> 00:10:14.950 align:middle line:84%
It wouldn't spread
throughout the brain.

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:17.075 align:middle line:84%
The patient wouldn't lose
generalized consciousness

00:10:17.075 --> 00:10:19.370 align:middle line:90%
and you would have helped.

00:10:19.370 --> 00:10:23.960 align:middle line:84%
>> Today Michael Gazzaniga is
a world-renowned neuroscientist

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:25.460 align:middle line:90%
and vineyard owner.

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:29.150 align:middle line:84%
In the 1960s, he was a
grad student participating

00:10:29.150 --> 00:10:31.160 align:middle line:90%
in radical brain experiments.

00:10:31.160 --> 00:10:33.770 align:middle line:84%
>> By sectioning this structure,
as can be seen in this half

00:10:33.770 --> 00:10:36.920 align:middle line:84%
brain section, called the corpus
callosum and it has over 2

00:10:36.920 --> 00:10:38.270 align:middle line:90%
million nerve fibers.

00:10:38.270 --> 00:10:42.110 align:middle line:84%
And they richly interconnect
the two halves of the brain.

00:10:42.110 --> 00:10:45.620 align:middle line:84%
What they did was, with
some trepidation initially,

00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:50.150 align:middle line:84%
to divide this corpus
callosum, the main pathway

00:10:50.150 --> 00:10:53.950 align:middle line:84%
by which the two
hemispheres communicate.

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:57.540 align:middle line:84%
And what they found after the
operation was that the seizures

00:10:57.540 --> 00:10:59.370 align:middle line:90%
largely stopped.

00:10:59.370 --> 00:11:02.370 align:middle line:84%
The other thing was it
was possible by setting

00:11:02.370 --> 00:11:04.920 align:middle line:84%
it up carefully
controlled experiments

00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:09.090 align:middle line:84%
to find out what the
reactions of the left

00:11:09.090 --> 00:11:12.670 align:middle line:84%
and the right hemisphere
were independently.

00:11:12.670 --> 00:11:15.880 align:middle line:84%
>> Each side of the brain
controls the opposite side

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:17.090 align:middle line:90%
of the body.

00:11:17.090 --> 00:11:19.660 align:middle line:84%
So the left hemisphere
controls the right side

00:11:19.660 --> 00:11:22.930 align:middle line:84%
of the body and the right
hemisphere communicates

00:11:22.930 --> 00:11:23.740 align:middle line:90%
with the left.

00:11:23.740 --> 00:11:26.890 align:middle line:90%


00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:28.990 align:middle line:84%
>> The patient
looks at a screen.

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:31.450 align:middle line:90%
Just imagine fixating on a dot.

00:11:31.450 --> 00:11:34.690 align:middle line:84%
And over here, we flash
a picture of an apple.

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:36.390 align:middle line:84%
So if it's in the
right visual field.

00:11:36.390 --> 00:11:38.140 align:middle line:90%
That goes to your left brain.

00:11:38.140 --> 00:11:39.960 align:middle line:84%
Left brain's got
language and speech.

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:42.250 align:middle line:90%
Patient said that's an apple.

00:11:42.250 --> 00:11:45.200 align:middle line:84%
This time, you put the apple
over in the left visual field.

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:49.890 align:middle line:84%
That now goes to the
right disconnected brain.

00:11:49.890 --> 00:11:53.370 align:middle line:84%
And you say to the
patient, what did you see?

00:11:53.370 --> 00:11:55.268 align:middle line:84%
And the patient says,
I didn't see anything.

00:11:55.268 --> 00:11:56.310 align:middle line:10%
>> Something on the left.

00:11:56.310 --> 00:11:57.110 align:middle line:10%
I know what it is.

00:11:57.110 --> 00:11:58.650 align:middle line:10%
I can't say it.

00:11:58.650 --> 00:12:00.796 align:middle line:10%
I want to, but I can't.

00:12:00.796 --> 00:12:01.870 align:middle line:10%
I know what it is.

00:12:01.870 --> 00:12:03.570 align:middle line:10%
>> What's it have to do with?

00:12:03.570 --> 00:12:06.730 align:middle line:10%
>> I can't tell
you that, either.

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:11.740 align:middle line:84%
>> They found that the left arm
and the right arm seem to be

00:12:11.740 --> 00:12:13.340 align:middle line:90%
contradicting one another.

00:12:13.340 --> 00:12:16.147 align:middle line:84%
So if somebody would select
a dress with her right arm,

00:12:16.147 --> 00:12:18.730 align:middle line:84%
then the left arm would take it
back, and put it on the shelf,

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:20.440 align:middle line:90%
and take out another one.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:22.060 align:middle line:90%
>> Frustrated.

00:12:22.060 --> 00:12:25.030 align:middle line:84%
>> The experiments proved
that we have two brains

00:12:25.030 --> 00:12:25.990 align:middle line:90%
in our heads.

00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:27.250 align:middle line:90%
Not just one.

00:12:27.250 --> 00:12:31.420 align:middle line:84%
But they do not see
the world the same way.

00:12:31.420 --> 00:12:33.940 align:middle line:84%
>> When I started
to do psychiatry,

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:37.060 align:middle line:84%
nothing much was said about
what the mass of the right

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:38.290 align:middle line:90%
hemisphere did.

00:12:38.290 --> 00:12:40.420 align:middle line:84%
My training was that
the left hemisphere

00:12:40.420 --> 00:12:44.050 align:middle line:84%
was very important for
understanding and language

00:12:44.050 --> 00:12:45.670 align:middle line:90%
and for speaking language.

00:12:45.670 --> 00:12:49.000 align:middle line:84%
But that really, what went
on in the right hemisphere

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.130 align:middle line:90%
was not that significant.

00:12:52.130 --> 00:12:57.700 align:middle line:84%
Michael Gazzaniga had said
that the right hemisphere

00:12:57.700 --> 00:12:59.980 align:middle line:84%
of the human brain had
about as much intelligence

00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:02.080 align:middle line:90%
as a chimpanzee.

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:04.510 align:middle line:90%
And so that wasn't encouraging.

00:13:04.510 --> 00:13:06.290 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I used
to give a lecture.

00:13:06.290 --> 00:13:09.340 align:middle line:84%
The left hemisphere, don't
leave home without it.

00:13:09.340 --> 00:13:11.980 align:middle line:84%
And that summarized
the importance

00:13:11.980 --> 00:13:15.760 align:middle line:84%
I saw to the special
modules, we call now systems,

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:16.780 align:middle line:90%
in the left hemisphere.

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:19.750 align:middle line:84%
That's where the heavy
duty lifting comes

00:13:19.750 --> 00:13:21.310 align:middle line:90%
for our complex cognitive life.

00:13:21.310 --> 00:13:24.120 align:middle line:90%


00:13:24.120 --> 00:13:27.500 align:middle line:84%
>> But in this experiment
with a split brain patient,

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:30.710 align:middle line:84%
while the right hemisphere
is trying to make the cube,

00:13:30.710 --> 00:13:35.000 align:middle line:84%
the left hemisphere's
hand keeps interfering.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:36.860 align:middle line:84%
Because it doesn't
know what it's doing.

00:13:36.860 --> 00:13:40.220 align:middle line:90%


00:13:40.220 --> 00:13:43.070 align:middle line:84%
Yet, the right
hemisphere on its own

00:13:43.070 --> 00:13:45.065 align:middle line:90%
solves the problem in seconds.

00:13:45.065 --> 00:13:48.080 align:middle line:90%


00:13:48.080 --> 00:13:50.720 align:middle line:84%
>> All of those who were
involved in the team came

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:53.300 align:middle line:84%
to the conclusion that each
hemisphere had, if you like,

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:57.910 align:middle line:84%
like a different way of
looking at the world.

00:13:57.910 --> 00:13:59.410 align:middle line:84%
>> You separate the
two hemispheres,

00:13:59.410 --> 00:14:01.230 align:middle line:84%
you've got mine left,
you got mine right.

00:14:01.230 --> 00:14:03.090 align:middle line:84%
It's what grabbed
everybody's interest.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:05.080 align:middle line:90%
Everybody can understand that.

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:08.310 align:middle line:84%
And so the left talks
and is analytical

00:14:08.310 --> 00:14:11.640 align:middle line:84%
and the right is creative
and pulls stuff together.

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:13.200 align:middle line:90%
And boom.

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:15.030 align:middle line:90%
It was an industry.

00:14:15.030 --> 00:14:16.990 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:14:16.990 --> 00:14:20.860 align:middle line:84%
>> Thanks to pop psychology,
the right and left hemispheres

00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:23.050 align:middle line:90%
became cartoon characters.

00:14:23.050 --> 00:14:26.650 align:middle line:84%
It was no longer
considered serious science.

00:14:26.650 --> 00:14:29.890 align:middle line:10%
>> The left does language and
reason and the right does airy,

00:14:29.890 --> 00:14:31.315 align:middle line:10%
fairy pictures of image.

00:14:31.315 --> 00:14:33.460 align:middle line:84%
And that turned out
not to be right.

00:14:33.460 --> 00:14:35.890 align:middle line:84%
Because what people
found was that over time,

00:14:35.890 --> 00:14:37.750 align:middle line:84%
it was obvious that
each hemisphere

00:14:37.750 --> 00:14:39.580 align:middle line:90%
engages in everything.

00:14:39.580 --> 00:14:41.740 align:middle line:84%
So each hemisphere--
right and left--

00:14:41.740 --> 00:14:45.730 align:middle line:84%
is involved in reason and
in language and in emotion.

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:47.800 align:middle line:90%
But in crucially different ways.

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:51.490 align:middle line:90%


00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:54.370 align:middle line:84%
>> Although the pop culture
understanding of the left

00:14:54.370 --> 00:14:57.040 align:middle line:84%
and right hemisphere
was eventually rejected,

00:14:57.040 --> 00:15:00.160 align:middle line:84%
a central question
still remained.

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:04.360 align:middle line:84%
>> Why does the brain have
two centers of consciousness,

00:15:04.360 --> 00:15:08.050 align:middle line:84%
each capable of maintaining
consciousness on its own

00:15:08.050 --> 00:15:11.020 align:middle line:84%
involved in everything,
but in a different way?

00:15:11.020 --> 00:15:19.620 align:middle line:90%


00:15:19.620 --> 00:15:22.530 align:middle line:84%
But it was only when I came to
look at the animal literature

00:15:22.530 --> 00:15:24.960 align:middle line:90%
that just, the penny dropped.

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:26.640 align:middle line:90%
Professor Gunturkun.

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:27.930 align:middle line:90%
>> Hey, Iain.

00:15:27.930 --> 00:15:29.710 align:middle line:90%
>> How nice of you to see me.

00:15:29.710 --> 00:15:30.510 align:middle line:90%
>> Absolutely.

00:15:30.510 --> 00:15:30.810 align:middle line:90%
Fantastic.

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:31.650 align:middle line:90%
How are you, Iain?

00:15:31.650 --> 00:15:32.520 align:middle line:90%
>> Lovely to meet you.

00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:33.300 align:middle line:90%
>> Absolutely.

00:15:33.300 --> 00:15:34.100 align:middle line:90%
Same with me.

00:15:34.100 --> 00:15:36.360 align:middle line:90%
>> I apologize for delays.

00:15:36.360 --> 00:15:37.660 align:middle line:90%
>> No problem at all.

00:15:37.660 --> 00:15:38.820 align:middle line:10%
This university is a maze.

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:40.500 align:middle line:10%
>> Just completely lost.

00:15:40.500 --> 00:15:42.270 align:middle line:90%
>> It's an absolute maze.

00:15:42.270 --> 00:15:45.990 align:middle line:84%
>> Dr. Onur Gunturkun is a
leading researcher in the field

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:47.700 align:middle line:90%
of animal neurology.

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:52.890 align:middle line:84%
He focuses on how birds use
each half of their brain.

00:15:52.890 --> 00:15:55.020 align:middle line:84%
>> These are the animals
with the eye rings.

00:15:55.020 --> 00:15:56.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Using the Velcro, you
can cover one eye at a time.

00:15:56.900 --> 00:15:57.325 align:middle line:90%
>> Exactly.

00:15:57.325 --> 00:15:57.750 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:15:57.750 --> 00:15:59.640 align:middle line:84%
So there is a little
cap that we have.

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:03.660 align:middle line:84%
And then the animal just sees
with its left or right eye.

00:16:03.660 --> 00:16:06.520 align:middle line:84%
Because, as you know, the
optic nerves cross completely.

00:16:06.520 --> 00:16:07.320 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:09.630 align:middle line:84%
>> So everything the right
eye sees goes to the left

00:16:09.630 --> 00:16:12.660 align:middle line:90%
hemisphere and vise versa.

00:16:12.660 --> 00:16:15.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Gunturkun devised a test
where pigeons were trained

00:16:15.570 --> 00:16:19.680 align:middle line:84%
to recognize human beings
in vacation photos.

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:21.690 align:middle line:84%
Each time the birds
recognized there

00:16:21.690 --> 00:16:25.590 align:middle line:84%
was a person in a picture,
they were rewarded.

00:16:25.590 --> 00:16:30.480 align:middle line:10%
>> After a while, they start to
understand there are pictures

00:16:30.480 --> 00:16:33.840 align:middle line:10%
with humans and there are
pictures without humans.

00:16:33.840 --> 00:16:37.200 align:middle line:10%
>> But then the birds were
given a harder challenge.

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:40.140 align:middle line:10%
>> Now we can start
to alter the pictures.

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:44.880 align:middle line:10%
We cut out the head, we cut out
the arm, we cut out the trunk,

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:47.460 align:middle line:10%
and spread it
across the picture.

00:16:47.460 --> 00:16:49.830 align:middle line:90%
It is like a slaughtering scene.

00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:52.200 align:middle line:84%
We take the pictures
and chop them

00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:55.170 align:middle line:84%
in smaller and smaller
and smaller pieces.

00:16:55.170 --> 00:16:57.750 align:middle line:90%
The left hemisphere says, OK.

00:16:57.750 --> 00:16:58.660 align:middle line:90%
I see a head.

00:16:58.660 --> 00:16:59.460 align:middle line:90%
I see eyes.

00:16:59.460 --> 00:17:00.360 align:middle line:90%
I see a nose.

00:17:00.360 --> 00:17:01.160 align:middle line:90%
That's a human.

00:17:01.160 --> 00:17:02.490 align:middle line:10%
I'm packing on it.

00:17:02.490 --> 00:17:06.810 align:middle line:10%
The right hemisphere now says,
this is no human anymore.

00:17:06.810 --> 00:17:10.440 align:middle line:10%
The right hemisphere
requires the correct position

00:17:10.440 --> 00:17:14.160 align:middle line:10%
of the human body to
recognize the human.

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:18.810 align:middle line:84%
So that means both hemispheres
are doing an excellent job.

00:17:18.810 --> 00:17:21.030 align:middle line:90%
Both hemispheres contribute.

00:17:21.030 --> 00:17:24.750 align:middle line:84%
And both hemispheres can
decide human or non-human,

00:17:24.750 --> 00:17:27.329 align:middle line:84%
but they do it with different
cognitive strategies.

00:17:27.329 --> 00:17:29.880 align:middle line:90%


00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:33.280 align:middle line:84%
When pigeons are
up to find food,

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:38.310 align:middle line:84%
they have to discriminate
grain from pebbles.

00:17:38.310 --> 00:17:41.280 align:middle line:84%
So that one hemisphere
is really concentrating

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:43.620 align:middle line:84%
on the tiny little
details of the food,

00:17:43.620 --> 00:17:46.950 align:middle line:84%
while the other one is
glancing into the environment.

00:17:46.950 --> 00:17:53.860 align:middle line:84%
And is on quick alert if an
aerial predator is coming.

00:17:53.860 --> 00:17:55.720 align:middle line:84%
>> This is fundamental
to survival.

00:17:55.720 --> 00:17:58.570 align:middle line:84%
And that was the moment
at which I realized

00:17:58.570 --> 00:18:03.400 align:middle line:84%
this is profoundly
important to all beings that

00:18:03.400 --> 00:18:09.420 align:middle line:84%
have to solve the conundrum
of how to eat and stay alive.

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:12.800 align:middle line:84%
>> McGilchrist realized
that in human beings,

00:18:12.800 --> 00:18:15.550 align:middle line:84%
these two different kinds of
attention played out in much

00:18:15.550 --> 00:18:17.740 align:middle line:90%
more complex ways.

00:18:17.740 --> 00:18:21.520 align:middle line:84%
>> You won't find a neurologist
anywhere in the world who will

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:23.950 align:middle line:84%
dispute that there is different
kinds of attention paid

00:18:23.950 --> 00:18:27.550 align:middle line:84%
by the left and
right hemisphere.

00:18:27.550 --> 00:18:30.280 align:middle line:84%
Then, very clearly,
each hemisphere

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:33.430 align:middle line:90%
must find a different world.

00:18:33.430 --> 00:18:37.470 align:middle line:84%
What would those two
worlds look like?

00:18:37.470 --> 00:18:41.350 align:middle line:84%
>> McGilchrist observed that the
left hemisphere gives a narrow,

00:18:41.350 --> 00:18:45.520 align:middle line:84%
sharply-focused
attention to detail.

00:18:45.520 --> 00:18:49.480 align:middle line:10%
Without understanding
the larger context.

00:18:49.480 --> 00:18:52.840 align:middle line:10%
It sees objects in relation
to their usefulness.

00:18:52.840 --> 00:18:55.510 align:middle line:84%
It's in charge of
the right hand, which

00:18:55.510 --> 00:18:57.860 align:middle line:84%
has the power to
manipulate things

00:18:57.860 --> 00:19:01.270 align:middle line:90%
such as tools and technology.

00:19:01.270 --> 00:19:04.570 align:middle line:84%
But it can't make
human connections.

00:19:04.570 --> 00:19:07.390 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't understand
relationships, humor,

00:19:07.390 --> 00:19:09.550 align:middle line:90%
tone of voice.

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:12.790 align:middle line:84%
Things and people are not
unique and individual.

00:19:12.790 --> 00:19:15.280 align:middle line:84%
But groups that it
can organize, sort,

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:18.970 align:middle line:84%
and file in a system of
rules and linear connections.

00:19:18.970 --> 00:19:24.630 align:middle line:90%


00:19:24.630 --> 00:19:27.780 align:middle line:84%
On its own, it has no
sense of the whole.

00:19:27.780 --> 00:19:30.900 align:middle line:84%
Even people are
seen as body parts.

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:33.990 align:middle line:84%
The world of the left
hemisphere is lifeless.

00:19:33.990 --> 00:19:37.290 align:middle line:84%
It shatters the world
into an assortment of bits

00:19:37.290 --> 00:19:39.840 align:middle line:90%
without meaning.

00:19:39.840 --> 00:19:42.600 align:middle line:84%
The right hemisphere,
by contrast,

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:46.330 align:middle line:84%
sees the broad
view of the world.

00:19:46.330 --> 00:19:47.730 align:middle line:90%
It is the master of the brain.

00:19:47.730 --> 00:19:51.900 align:middle line:90%


00:19:51.900 --> 00:19:54.570 align:middle line:84%
It perceives an
interconnected world.

00:19:54.570 --> 00:19:57.910 align:middle line:84%
It understands
relationships, body language,

00:19:57.910 --> 00:20:00.570 align:middle line:84%
facial expression,
and implicit meaning.

00:20:00.570 --> 00:20:04.250 align:middle line:90%


00:20:04.250 --> 00:20:07.580 align:middle line:84%
The right hemisphere
engages with life,

00:20:07.580 --> 00:20:10.455 align:middle line:84%
understands movement,
story, and metaphor.

00:20:10.455 --> 00:20:15.480 align:middle line:90%


00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:19.515 align:middle line:84%
It forces how humanity fits
into the whole of creation.

00:20:19.515 --> 00:20:22.710 align:middle line:90%


00:20:22.710 --> 00:20:25.560 align:middle line:84%
The divided brain
gives us two types

00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:30.570 align:middle line:84%
of attention, two ways of
engaging with the world.

00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:35.290 align:middle line:84%
It has made us the most
powerful species on Earth.

00:20:35.290 --> 00:20:39.990 align:middle line:90%


00:20:39.990 --> 00:20:43.110 align:middle line:84%
But the left hemisphere's
narrow kind of attention

00:20:43.110 --> 00:20:51.390 align:middle line:84%
reminded McGilchrist of
something else, our world.

00:20:51.390 --> 00:20:53.840 align:middle line:90%
[TRAIN TRACKS]

00:20:53.840 --> 00:21:03.150 align:middle line:90%


00:21:03.150 --> 00:21:05.480 align:middle line:10%
>> I began thinking
about how in public life,

00:21:05.480 --> 00:21:09.870 align:middle line:10%
everything has become more
regulated, more rule-bound,

00:21:09.870 --> 00:21:10.670 align:middle line:10%
more explicit.

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:15.290 align:middle line:90%


00:21:15.290 --> 00:21:19.520 align:middle line:84%
For the last 100 years, a way
of thinking which is reductive,

00:21:19.520 --> 00:21:21.670 align:middle line:90%
mechanistic has taken us over.

00:21:21.670 --> 00:21:25.070 align:middle line:90%


00:21:25.070 --> 00:21:28.400 align:middle line:84%
It's enabled us to manipulate
the world, to grab resources,

00:21:28.400 --> 00:21:30.230 align:middle line:90%
to become wealthy.

00:21:30.230 --> 00:21:34.270 align:middle line:90%


00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:38.290 align:middle line:84%
But it's also meant that
we've lost the means

00:21:38.290 --> 00:21:40.360 align:middle line:84%
to feel satisfaction
and fulfillment

00:21:40.360 --> 00:21:42.715 align:middle line:90%
through our place in the world.

00:21:42.715 --> 00:21:45.770 align:middle line:90%


00:21:45.770 --> 00:21:47.810 align:middle line:84%
And we created
outside ourselves,

00:21:47.810 --> 00:21:51.470 align:middle line:84%
a world which, very much,
looked like the interior world

00:21:51.470 --> 00:21:53.480 align:middle line:90%
of the left hemisphere.

00:21:53.480 --> 00:21:57.470 align:middle line:84%
Rigid lines of things
that were rolled out

00:21:57.470 --> 00:22:00.980 align:middle line:84%
mechanically and
were non-unique.

00:22:00.980 --> 00:22:05.400 align:middle line:90%


00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:08.820 align:middle line:90%
Bureaucracy is in its element.

00:22:08.820 --> 00:22:13.110 align:middle line:84%
It depends on qualities which
the left hemisphere provide--

00:22:13.110 --> 00:22:19.650 align:middle line:84%
organized ability, anonymity,
standardization, uniformity,

00:22:19.650 --> 00:22:21.390 align:middle line:90%
abstraction, and so on.

00:22:21.390 --> 00:22:23.970 align:middle line:90%


00:22:23.970 --> 00:22:27.240 align:middle line:84%
Systems designed to
maximize utility,

00:22:27.240 --> 00:22:30.840 align:middle line:84%
there will be a loss
of cohesion socially

00:22:30.840 --> 00:22:33.120 align:middle line:84%
because the left
hemisphere needs control.

00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:36.270 align:middle line:84%
And there's a lack of
trust and a lot of paranoia

00:22:36.270 --> 00:22:40.860 align:middle line:84%
that we need for CCTV and
monitoring of all kinds.

00:22:40.860 --> 00:22:43.260 align:middle line:10%
[TYPING]

00:22:43.260 --> 00:22:49.020 align:middle line:90%


00:22:49.020 --> 00:22:51.210 align:middle line:84%
The left hemisphere is
the quick and dirty one.

00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:53.190 align:middle line:90%
Because it has to make action.

00:22:53.190 --> 00:22:54.960 align:middle line:84%
It likes things to
be black and white.

00:22:54.960 --> 00:22:59.490 align:middle line:84%
What do you mean there's half
or ambiguity or metaphor?

00:22:59.490 --> 00:23:00.960 align:middle line:90%
I want to know the facts.

00:23:00.960 --> 00:23:03.300 align:middle line:90%
It's like this or it's that.

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:06.330 align:middle line:84%
People think, well, the
left hemisphere is surely,

00:23:06.330 --> 00:23:07.710 align:middle line:90%
the basis for our intelligence.

00:23:07.710 --> 00:23:10.770 align:middle line:84%
It's the one that does
all that analysis.

00:23:10.770 --> 00:23:12.520 align:middle line:84%
But actually, this
is not the case.

00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:15.120 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot of evidence
that the really critical one

00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:17.070 align:middle line:84%
from a point of
view of intelligence

00:23:17.070 --> 00:23:20.020 align:middle line:90%
is the right hemisphere.

00:23:20.020 --> 00:23:22.450 align:middle line:84%
Another important difference--
a very important one--

00:23:22.450 --> 00:23:25.060 align:middle line:84%
is that between fixity
and flow, so things

00:23:25.060 --> 00:23:27.160 align:middle line:84%
in the left
hemisphere are fixed.

00:23:27.160 --> 00:23:29.920 align:middle line:84%
Whereas in the right
hemisphere, flow

00:23:29.920 --> 00:23:33.640 align:middle line:90%
is what it sees and understands.

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:35.800 align:middle line:90%
Now, that is very profound.

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:39.280 align:middle line:84%
That actually changes the
whole nature of what life is.

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:41.270 align:middle line:90%
Nothing is just isolated.

00:23:41.270 --> 00:23:42.880 align:middle line:90%
It is always part of a flow.

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:44.920 align:middle line:84%
Things can only be
understood in context.

00:23:44.920 --> 00:23:46.960 align:middle line:84%
When you take them
out, they change.

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:49.690 align:middle line:84%
When you grab them and put them
in the spotlight of attention

00:23:49.690 --> 00:23:52.210 align:middle line:84%
and make them explicit,
they change their nature.

00:23:52.210 --> 00:23:53.800 align:middle line:90%
Jokes, for example.

00:23:53.800 --> 00:23:55.490 align:middle line:90%
Sex, for example.

00:23:55.490 --> 00:23:57.361 align:middle line:90%
Religion, for example.

00:23:57.361 --> 00:23:59.716 align:middle line:90%
